bug.short_desc: Add support for Tomcat 6.0.x

long_desc.thetext:
Might as well go ahead and create an enhancement request for this.
Upon initial inspection, the current Tomcat 5.5 support seems fairly close. There are a couple of new issues discovered so far. A minor one is that the HTTP connector has the protocol set to "HTTP/1.0". The current connector handling looks for just "HTTP", so it doesn't find the HTTP port.
A bigger change in Tomcat 6.0.x is that all the Tomcat jars come in a single "lib" directory. If the user wants to prevent webapps from accessing server classes, it appears they can enable a security manager and package access to "org.apache.catalina" and other appropriate packages will be denied. This does create an issue with the Tomcat runtime in that taking all jars in the "lib" directory will mean server classes will be available for code completions, which would be good to avoid. I will plan on at least filtering the jars to exclude the jars with server classes and perhaps provide some ability for the user to configure which jars are included or excluded.
Tim, Please assign this one to me. Also, if you think the ability to configure runtime jars deserves wider scope, let me know. Thanks.

Yup, looks good. I'm a fan of incremental development, so please feel free to release once you've got initial support working (a server name like "Tomcat v6.0 (work in progress)" might help) and then progressively improve/finish it.
Do you know when the official 6.0 release date is? Google couldn't find it for me, so I wasn't sure it existed. ;-)
For the runtime jars, most other servers haven't been as thoughtful as Tomcat and already have one or more directories with API/internal jars mixed. In most cases, the adapter has a fixed list and only puts the API jars on the classpath. This list is at least in a text/property file in the plugin instead of code so that people aren't stuck if the server adds new jars and we don't have a fix out yet.
This is probably the minimum we should do, but if you have some fresh ideas or a better way to configure it, I'm open to it.

As for an "official" release date, there really isn't one. When the urge get strong enough, a release gets cut. The release then gets a vote on it's stability. The "official" release could be considered the first one voted "stable", as opposed to "beta" or "alpha", which technically could happen on any release. I would guess that there may be one or two more "betas", then the odds will go up noticeably for the next one achieving "stable". I hope to commit the initial implementation between M4 and M5.

The initial implementation has been released and will appear in the next integration build for WTP 2.0 M5. The Server 2.5 support isn't available yet, so the implementation will need to be updated once that is available.
Also, filtering of the runtime jars as mentioned in the Description is not yet implemented. I still need to figure out how it might best be done.
Since the work isn't finished, I'll keep this enhancement open for now. I probably won't keep it open past M5 release if there is nothing major still missing. I'll open new bugs for the missing pieces.
Note that with the jars all in the "lib" directory, I believe preventing webapp classes from accessing server classes is now accomplished using a security manager. In earlier Tomcats, it was accomplished using separate classloaders and didn't require a security manager. I'm not sure how many might reconfigure their Tomcat 6.0 to be like the earlier Tomcat's to restore this behavior. Doing so would break the current implementation which only supports the default "lib" configuration. I may look into incorporating the catalina.properties settings into the version checking code to expand what it can handle. It's not a high priority though.

Since this is working and in a milestone I think we should close this enhancement out instead of leaving it open and targeted to a previous milestone. If there are bugs or further enhancements we should open new bugs.

Just FYI, today Tomcat 6.0.10 was declared the first production-quality release for 6.0.x series.

Hi Scott,
No, none. In order to dual license effectively, the author would need to own all of the copyright or have the permission of all other copyright holders to license under any particular license. Following the specification of the format statement for Fortran 77 [1], I believe a partial grammar for it could be expressed as:
format:= line FORMAT ( flist ) flist := fexpr | flist , fexpr fexpr := r ed | ed ed := m w . d
where r is a repeat count, m is a character indicating the manner of editing, e.g. "F" or "E", and w and d are non-zero, unsigned integers.
Consider the below Fortran 77 (fixed-form) program:
program Hello 10 format(F5.4,3E2.1) end
The statement in this program should satisfy the grammar above. It compiles using the Intel Fortran compiler 9.1, and GNU G77 3.4.6.
However, parsing this in Photran gives only the skull in the Outline view (and no parsing debug information despite having checked those preferences -- where do they go?).
The offending token seems to be the repeat count in the second format expression (having a repeat count in the first format expression causes no problem).

bug.short_desc: Mylar startup issues/plugin circular references

long_desc.thetext:
Hi folks, I think I finally discovered the root cause of the dreadful startup bug ("thread "Worker-X" timed out waiting (5000ms) for thread "Worker-Y" to finish starting bundle "org.eclipse.mylar.tasks.ui").
Warning: this is a very long bug... In fact there are a set of bugs working together to make this happen (or not, according to the situation; explanation bellow):
1 - Mylar plugins are doing expensive operations on Bundle.start():
I see that tasks.ui plugin do many heavy-weight operations like reading the tasklist (which involves XML parsing) on plugin start() method.
This type of operation must be made on a background job because the platform has a timeout of 5 seconds for each plugin initialization. The BundleActivator.start() javadoc explicitly says that this method MUST return quickly.
2 - Mylar plugins are doing expensive operations on Display.asyncExec():
Taking a quick look, I see that at least context.ui, tasks.ui and mylar.team invoke Display.asyncExec() { [long-chain-of-method-calls] }.
The problem here is that asyncExec() forces the Runnable to be executed on UI thread. If the Runnable takes much time to complete, this causes UI to freeze. Probably this is the cause of UI freeze on Eclipse initialization I see.
The worst case here is on tasks.ui. Instead of simply wrapping a code block inside asyncExec(), we must track down the call stack and identify what methods requires to be executed on UI thread, and wrap just them with asyncExec.
3 - There is a circular dependency between context.core and tasks.ui:
This is the worst bug. Tasks UI depends on context.core == OK. However, there is a "involuntary" dependency of context core on tasks UI, because tasks UI provides a context store extension, so context core activation triggers tasks UI activation while loading context store extensions, and vice-versa.
I think the easiest way to fix this is to move the filesystem-based context store implementation to its own plugin like I suggested on bug#160356 (I'm suposing that the filesystem context store does not have any dependency on tasks UI classes).
This way, this new plugin (let's call it "context.filesystem.store") would depend only on context.core. Context core activation would only trigger context.filesystem.core activation. Tasks UI activation would trigger context.core and so on.
Conclusion: there is a lot of problems contributing to make this bug happen sometimes.
Sometimes, depending on VM classloading policy, and because of busy BundleActivator.start() implementations, bug (1) can be triggered causing the plugin init timeout.
Most times, bug (2) is causing bug (3) to NOT happen. I suppose that asyncExec() would be masquerading the circular dependency, otherwise tasks UI would trigger context core activation, which would trigger tasks UI, and so on. Probably the "trigger" code would be inside a asyncExec() block, so it is scheduled to run on UI thread, letting the plugin complete initialization.
However, on some VMs/OSs the thread policy can be different, making the deadlock/plugin timeout happen.
Taking a quick look at my bug list, I can remember strong candidates for being dups of this:
- bug#159706 - mylar fails to start on BEA jrockit VM - bug#167320 - More startup errors after upgrading to 1.0.0 test
To investigate:
- bug#167639 - 1.0 Errors on Startup. - all bugs containing "thread "Worker-X" timed out waiting (5000ms) for thread "Worker-Y" to finish starting bundle blablabla" on stack trace.
So, fixing these 3 problems would end the timeout problems.

Thanks for excellent analysis Willian, I think that you got the nail on the head. We haven't seen this problem for a while, so I'm still wondering what triggers it (e.g. large number of plug-ins activating, very slow machine or pinned CPU). Our previous laziness improvements made it better but did not solve it (1), and without making huge changes we will still some eagerness to ensure that all externalizers are loaded. But I will definitely plan to do (3) for 1.0.1 to address this, and hope to make some improvements on the others.

Yes, fixing (3) is relatively low-risk and easy for 1.0.1 and would handle the worst case.
We'll still probably see some (1) cases occurring, but the changes needed to fix (1) and (2) are very risk to do in a so short iteration like 1.0.1.
We can revisit this on 2.x stream, since these are performance bugs too.

Willian: it looks like you have found a bug that's different than that given by the description here, because it has to do with the fact that the MylarTeamPlugin reads extensions during it's start method. What I have done to fix that is move the extension point reading into the asyncExec of MylarTeam.Plugin.start(..), which will prevent the startup concurrency. These extension points do need to be initialized on the that plug-in's start method because they need to eagerly update the state of the change sets. I can give you a dev build to try this out, what version of Eclipse are you running? Fyi, I'm merging this change back into the 1.0 streams.

Willian: We use the asyncExecs(..) for the cases where we need the plug-in to do stuff at startup, i.e. where the preferred lazily initialization of extension points (or other plug-in state) does not work, but where the initializaiton should not hold up the initialization of the workbench (or causes problems when it does, as with the class loading bug). In the case of the team provider, not doing this at startup would mean that the change sets would not be probably updated to contain the Mylar elements, since we have to do some tricks to convert the existing change sets that Eclipse supports into the Mylar context change sets. But if you do encounter ways to improve on the initialization, please do post the ideas.

I'm doubt everyone is testing against every version that their range says will work but we simply can't take on the task of ensuring that and I doubt anyone can. This is one of a number of issues I have with the specifying of ranges without testing that what's specified is meaningful and correct. I'd rather not specify a range at all, but given the mandate to do so, we will choose to generate them strictly based on rules such as "the lower bound will be set to the version we built and tested against."
